    },
    {
        "type": "text",
        "text": "distinguishing features",
        "text_level": 2,
        "bbox": [
            161,
            575,
            322,
            592
        ],
        "page_idx": 0
    },
    {
        "type": "text",
        "text": "Arms usually break off central disc very easily.   \nDistinct spines protrude from aboral margin edge;   \narms long, flexible, flattened and tapering, strap-like.   \nUsually five arms.",
        "bbox": [
            161,
            592,
            489,
            650
        ],
        "page_idx": 0
    },
    {
        "type": "text",
        "text": "Colour",
        "text_level": 2,
        "bbox": [
            163,
            663,
            211,
            677
        ],
        "page_idx": 0
    },
    {
        "type": "text",
        "text": "Brown to dark pink.",
        "bbox": [
            161,
            678,
            290,
            693
        ],
        "page_idx": 0
    },
    {
        "type": "text",
        "text": "Size",
        "text_level": 2,
        "bbox": [
            163,
            706,
            194,
            721
        ],
        "page_idx": 0
    },
    {
        "type": "text",
        "text": "Average up to 150 mm diameter, but can get larger individuals.",
        "bbox": [
            161,
            722,
            487,
            751
        ],
        "page_idx": 0
    },
    {
        "type": "text",
        "text": "distribution",
        "text_level": 2,
        "bbox": [
            163,
            764,
            247,
            780
        ],
        "page_idx": 0
    },
    {
        "type": "text",
        "text": "Southern African endemic. West and South Coasts of South Africa, to Port Elizabeth; 54 m to 360+ m depth.",
        "bbox": [
            161,
            781,
            489,
            825
        ],
        "page_idx": 0
    },
    {
        "type": "text",
        "text": "Similar species",
        "text_level": 2,
        "bbox": [
            509,
            575,
            615,
            592
        ],
        "page_idx": 0
    },
    {
        "type": "text",
        "text": "Astropecten polyacanthus and Astropecten exilis, however arms of Luidia africana are more flattened and broader, i.e. less tapered, and break off central disc easily.",
        "bbox": [
            507,
            592,
            836,
            650
        ],
        "page_idx": 0
    },
