            836,
            279
        ],
        "page_idx": 3
    },
    {
        "type": "text",
        "text": "distinguishing features",
        "text_level": 2,
        "bbox": [
            161,
            575,
            322,
            592
        ],
        "page_idx": 3
    },
    {
        "type": "text",
        "text": "Short-armed, stellate body form with a reticular skeleton (spiky skeleton with soft tissue covering). Distinct raised spines covering the aboral surface 1-4 mm in length. Arms fairly rigid, with ends often turning upwards or curling inwards. Two rows of tube feet. Madreporite white in colour, located offcentre halfway to base of arms. Strong spines along the base of arms.",
        "bbox": [
            161,
            592,
            489,
            707
        ],
        "page_idx": 3
    },
    {
        "type": "text",
        "text": "Colour",
        "text_level": 2,
        "bbox": [
            161,
            719,
            211,
            734
        ],
        "page_idx": 3
    },
    {
        "type": "text",
        "text": "Deep orange to red or even pure white, with spines light red to yellowish white. Pale oral surface.",
        "bbox": [
            161,
            736,
            487,
            765
        ],
        "page_idx": 3
    },
    {
        "type": "text",
        "text": "Size",
        "text_level": 2,
        "bbox": [
            163,
            777,
            194,
            793
        ],
        "page_idx": 3
    },
    {
        "type": "text",
        "text": "Average 50 up to 160 mm diameter, mostly small specimens but occasionally large too.",
        "bbox": [
            161,
            794,
            487,
            824
        ],
        "page_idx": 3
    },
    {
        "type": "text",
        "text": "distribution",
        "text_level": 2,
        "bbox": [
            163,
            835,
            248,
            851
        ],
        "page_idx": 3
    },
    {
        "type": "text",
        "text": "South Atlantic including West Coast of South Africa.",
        "bbox": [
            161,
            852,
            487,
            868
        ],
        "page_idx": 3
    },
    {
        "type": "image",
        "img_path": "images/5540298c6937e792eb870be1377a589c1a4efcfece7b65a338b674a29614c6f6.jpg",
        "image_caption": [],
        "image_footnote": [],
        "bbox": [
            509,
            322,
            833,
            551
        ],
        "page_idx": 3
    },
    {
        "type": "text",
        "text": "Similar species",
        "text_level": 2,
        "bbox": [
            509,
            575,
            615,
            592
        ],
        "page_idx": 3
    },
    {
        "type": "text",
        "text": "Lophaster quadrispinus, which has many dense raised tubercles on the aboral surface or Diplopteraster multipes, which is more cushion-like, with arms that are not as clearly defined as P. echinaster.",
        "bbox": [
            507,
            592,
            836,
            650
        ],
        "page_idx": 3
    },
    {
        "type": "text",
        "text": "references",
        "text_level": 2,
        "bbox": [
